{"key":"processedPost-16026075","value":{"id":16026075,"first":16024489,"last":16026321,"when":1333246460,"utime":"04/01/12 05:14 AM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Disgruntled said:</strong><br />the second link on gypsums more like it, its only gypsum, its prilled form and not powder which is fine, you might have to.crush it up for certain things though.</blockquote><br />Pelleted gypsum is powder gypsum with a bonding agent added to make it granular so it will pass through machinery easier without jamming.&nbsp; Never crush it up.&nbsp; The bonding agent is water soluble and the gypsum will turn back to powder when wet.<br />Just a side note for those like me who are organic certified: The granular/pellet form of gypsum is not allowed by the USDA because of the bonding agent.&nbsp; You have to use gypsum flour, which is ground from solid rock and is pure.<br />RR"}}